SIMPLE: sturdy
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sturdy
<hw>Stur"dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sturdier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Sturdiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sturdi</ets>
inconsiderable, OF. <ets>estourdi</ets> stunned, giddy, thoughtless,
rash, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tourdi</ets>, p. p. of OF. <ets>estourdir</ets> to
stun, to render giddy, to amaze, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tourdir</ets>; of
uncertain origin. The sense has probably been influenced by E.
<ets>stout</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Foolishly obstinate or
resolute; stubborn; unrelenting; unfeeling; stern.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>sturdy</qex> marquis gan his hearte dress⟦br⟧
To rue upon her wifely steadfastness.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This must be done, and I would fain see⟦br⟧
Mortal so <qex>sturdy</qex> as to gainsay.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>sturdy</qex>, hardened sinner shall advance to the utmost
pitch of impiety with less reluctance than he took the first steps.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resolute, in a good sense; or firm, unyielding
quality; <as>as, a man of <ex>sturdy</ex> piety or
patriotism</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Characterized by physical strength or force; strong;
lusty; violent; <as>as, a <ex>sturdy</ex> lout</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How bowed the woods beneath their <qex>sturdy</qex> stroke!</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Stiff; stout; strong; <as>as, a <ex>sturdy</ex>
oak</as>.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was not of any delicate contexture; his limbs rather
<qex>sturdy</qex> than dainty.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H.
Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Hardy; stout; strong; firm; robust;
stiff.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1431 --></p>

<p><ent>Sturdy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sturdy
<hw>Stur"dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>estourdi</ets> giddiness, stupefaction.]</ety> <fld>(Vet.)</fld>
<def>A disease in sheep and cattle, marked by great nervousness, or by
dullness and stupor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sturgeon</ent>⟦br⟧
